It's beginning to look that way. The underlying theme of Hollywood movies is the same tripe over and over. The repetitiveness is quite worrying. Hypnosis works this way. You repeat something over and over until it's engraved on someones brain and accepted as factual even if it is in truth total rot. Like the nuclear gutter science thrown at the public by most of the movies, animations, books and television shows in this category. At first I thought it was just writers copying each other and making the most out of a convenient bogeyman. The ill understood and universally feared nuclear power spectre.<br>
However, back in the 60's nuclear power was seen as having a very bright future. Despite Hiroshima and Nagasaki still being fresh in peoples memories. Then the fearmongering began in the media. All forms of media. <br>
This is just too similar to the false presentation of Cannabis back in the 30's. The 'Marijuana: Assasin of Youth' media blitz which killed of the Hemp industry. America's number one largest cash crop was quietly done away with. The paper mills were behind this move and they successfully removed their only competition by using contacts within the Government and press.<br>
Now who would stand to gain by demonising nuclear power? The modern big boys capable of such a move and who wouldn't hesitate to pull out all stops would be the oil barons. Beyond doubt. Nuclear power would have been a threat to the fossil fuel industry back in the 60's. What better way to get rid of this competition than to fan the flames of fear. Sensationalise and ruthlessly portray any incident in the worst possible light. <br>
With money anything is possible and like I said, it wouldn't be the first time. The Hemp industry was eliminated within a year of the Decorticator being invented. A machine for automising Hemp fibre processing. It promised to supply paper 10 times cheaper than timber pulp. The Timber mills had two choices. Go bankrupt was one. The other was pull in favours from their best friends. Their major customers, the newspaper publishers and those politicians recieving campaign contributions annually in exchange for favourable legislation.  <br>
